 require real OS behavior.","test_description":"Set the XDG_CONFIG_HOME environment variable to a temporary directory, create a config file there, run the loader, and verify it reads from that directory and not from ~/.config. Check that the resolved path is correct on the current OS.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Real environment variables and actual filesystem paths are essential; mocking environ would hide if the code ignores XDG_CONFIG_HOME entirely.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When an environment variable with the TOOL_ prefix conflicts with a key in the config file, the environment variable value is used.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The merge logic (use environ if present) is deterministic, but the real failure is at the boundary: incorrect variable-name mapping (TOOL_DATABASE_HOST should map to database.host) or the override silently failing. Testing with real config file I/O and environment variables catches these mapping bugs that unit-level mocking would miss.","test_description":"Create a YAML config file with a value (e.g., database: { host: 'localhost' }), set TOOL_DATABASE_HOST environment variable to a different value, load the config, and verify the environ value overrides the file value.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Real file parsing plus actual environment variable handling together are needed; mocking both would miss bugs in variable-name mapping logic.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the config file contains a YAML syntax error, the error message includes the line number where the problem was detected.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real YAML parser (PyYAML, ruamel.yaml) is responsible for reporting line numbers in error objects. If we mock the parser, we can fake an error and the test passes even if our code accidentally strips the line number. We must use the real parser on a malformed file to verify the line number is correctly propagated through our error handling.","test_description":"Create a YAML file with a syntax error on a known line (e.g., bad indentation on line 5), load it, catch the exception, and verify the error message includes the correct line number.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Real YAML parser is essential; mocking it would hide if we drop the line number in error handling.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the config directory does not exist at startup, the loader creates it and writes a defaults file before proceeding.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"While the logic (if dir exists, skip; else create) is simple, real failures are OS-level: permission errors, defaults file content is incorrect, or directory creation fails. Testing with a real temp filesystem catches these edge cases. Mocking the filesystem would pass even if the code fails to handle write errors or uses wrong file permissions.","test_description":"Ensure the config directory does not exist (use a temp directory), run the loader, verify the directory was created, and verify the defaults file exists with correct structure and content. Check that no exceptions are raised.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Real filesystem I/O is essential; mocked I/O would miss permission errors, race conditions, and OS-specific failures in directory/file creation.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13548,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13548},"output_tokens":4,"ser